<br>
(Though why you would want to read my ramblings is totally beyond me.)<br>
<br>
This week has been a rather trying one (and it's only Wednesday). I've spent more time sleeping than doing anything else. That's what pain pills will do to you, I guess. Not that I mind - I love sleep. But I have a lot else to do, like taking my car into the shop, and writing out a couple of applications, and finishing a paper or two for school. But why worry about stuff like that, when there's sleep to be had and movies to be watched?<br>
<br>
When I wasn't asleep, I've been reading The Fellowship of the Ring. I've never read it before, and I'm trying to finish it before the next movie comes out. We'll see... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> MaiKana</span><br> <span class=usertitle><img src=http://www.plauder-smilies.de/person/krank.gif>A Stranger with No Real Name</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(11/14/02 10:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fchristlikebookloversfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Amy's Journal</span><hr size=1> LOL! Sleep is good. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/emoticons_classic/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub78.ezboard.com/bchristlikebooklovers.showUserPublicProfile?gid=redheadedgoddess>Redheaded Goddess</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><img src='http://imbiss-coding.de/smiliez.de/smz/tr/tr_34.gif'>CLBL Admin</span><br>  Posts: 517<br> <font color=#3333ff>(11/14/02 7:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fchristlikebookloversfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Amy's Journal</span><hr size=1> Ah yes, sleep is de best man! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub78.ezboard.com/bchristlikebooklovers.showUserPublicProfile?gid=femalenomad>FemaleNomad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CLBL Newbie ~ Welcome!</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#3333ff>(11/16/02 3:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fchristlikebookloversfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> 15 November</span><hr size=1> Well, I'm pretty much healed. (On a side note, I can't believe you guys are actually reading this! I guess it goes to show that we always think other people's lives are  more interesting than our own...or maybe we're all voyeurs at heart!) <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/emoticons_classic/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So that means no  more sleep all day, miss all my classes, miss work, and have an excuse for it anymore. Sigh. That was kind of fun. But only for a week, because I think if I was on total bedrest, I'd go insane. But of course  now I have a lot to catch up on. A LOT. And I am so tired of that. But I guess, being a procrastinator, that's what I get, huh?<br>
<br>
Today I was reminded of the power of prayer. I was talking to a friend in Australia about one of our mutual friends in London (yes, we're quite a cosmopolitan little group to come out of someplace like Michigan). And my London friend is just tortured by clinical depression. My first response was to pray for her. (Especially after reading the Faith Healing discussion in the God-Lovers forum.) I know that God hears my prayers and answers, but in my faith tradition (presbyterian) it is so easy to fall into the trap of &quot;God's will will win out, no matter what I  do.&quot; Which is true, of course. But it's just like with evangelism. Maybe it is God's will for me to pray for her and  pray for her healing? How dare I go against His will (or at least try - I don't think we can thwart His will)?<br>
<br>
WARNING: As this is my journal, I cannot be held responsible for the randomness of my thoughts recorded here. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.plauder-smilies.de/happy.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Anyway, I just want to pray and pray for my friend.<br>
<br>
...Well, that's not exactly true. I want to call her and go see her and tell her everything's going to be okay. A lot of her depression stems from this need to be perfect, like her sister, this need to live up to a totally unrealistic goal. And when one thing goes wrong - snowball effect, and she drowns in it. She actually left college my senior year because she couldn't handle it anymore.Nothing big, just a million little things.<br>
<br>
And it sounds like she's going that way again. Little job troubles, little  marriage troubles, little health issues - and it just overwhelms her. <br>
<br>
But what can you do for a person struggling with depression? I mean, unless you're going through it yourself, it's practically impossible to understand. And I am an  optimist by nature.<br>
<br>
(I think the Lord's trying to teach me compassion.)<br>
<br>
Anyway. I wil write to her  later, and send her a good book. (It's a Vera Wang wedding book, full of BEAUTIFUL pics. She's a fashion designer, and her specialty is wedding dresses, so I think Vera Wang'll be a good prize.)<br>
<br>
Right now I am planning  my trip to Australia. I'm going  to visit my friend there. I can't wait! Only 2 more months! I've never been to Australia, so I'm way excited. It'll be my 12th country. I have a list of 100 countries I want to visit in my lifetime, so, this'll be another one checked off my list. Of course, that's not the only reason to go. (I also wantto fill up my passport before I have to get a new one in 4 years.) And I want to see my friends again. <br>
<br>
You know how there are just a few people in your life who are going to be your friends for ever? Well, I'm not speaking from the wisdom of the ages or anything, but in my experience, there are just some people who are going to be your friends forever, and they'll always be there for you, even if they're on the other side of the world. I have a few: in Chicago, London, and Melbourne. The  closest one is almost 3000 miles away from me. But that just doesn't even matter. It's cool to know that they are there for me - and I am there for them.<br>
<br>
Okay, before I get all maudlin (it IS pretty late), let us change the subject. Let's talk about some books.<br>
<br>
I am reading, like I said, Fellowship of the Ring. I'm also reading On the Road (Jack Kerouac), which I've never read before. And FastFood Nation, which is about the seamy underbelly of the fast food empire. Kind of interesting. <br>
<br>
I also just finished In a Sunburned Country, by Bill Bryson. If you didn't already know, I LOVE travel books. Especially travel literature (you know, stories about people's travels to other places?). And Bill Bryson is the funniest. Seriously. I read his books at work, and everyone knows when I'm reading one, because I can't help but giggle. They laugh at me, but there you go. I don't mind. Every once in awhile a vulgar word will slip in, but mostly his books are just hilarious. Especially if you've been to the places he's describing. He has one on the US called The Lost Continent. If you haven't traveled outside the US, but you know all about small towns in the Midwest, pick this one up. It's great. Then, once you're hooked, there are several more, all excellent fun.<br>
<br>
I could talk and talk about books, but for now I shan't. It's almost 3AM, and I still haven't gone to sleep. (So much for the warning label on my drugs. May Cause Drowsiness indeed!) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub78.ezboard.com/bchristlikebooklovers.showUserPublicProfile?gid=femalenomad>FemaleNomad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezWannabe</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#3333ff>(11/19/02 11:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fchristlikebookloversfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> 19th</span><hr size=1> Okay, here's a HUGE answer to prayer - my loan check finally came in!!! Which means I can actually pay my rent AND buy groceries - all in the same week!<br>
<br>
So...maybe that's not terribly exciting to you, but believe me, it's been a challenge living on my wages lately. Because my rent is more than half my take-home pay for the month. Oh well...<br>
<br>
Ugh. I am so challenged by the topics here at GLO, sometimes. All this deep thinking gives me a bit of a headache. In a good way, of course, but still...sometimes I don't WANT to think. Oh well. It's good for me. Makes me more honest, and it makes me really understand why I believe what I do and how I do. And that's a good thing.<br>
<br>
Still...<br>
<br>
Here's another answer to prayer. I got into a great religious discussion with a couple of people at work today. I am the resident bible authority (which isn't saying much), so I get into these discussions a lot. Today it was about women in ministry. I am still not sure what I think about that. Hmm...maybe I should ask some GLOers for their thoughts? Later. The cool thing about these conversations is that I get to share openly about my faith, and the conversations inevitably lead around to the Gospel...it is so cool. Especially since I REALLY do not like doing initiative evangelism. But when I can share the gospel as a result of a conversation - wow! I mean, you just have to know it's God working. Awesome.<br>
<br>
Hmm...I have a lot of work to do - a couple of papers to write, and a movie to watch - but I don't want to quite yet. <br>
<br>
You know, sometimes I wonder what I'm doing here at GLO. Because I disagree with so much of the common thought, I feel like all I'm doing is arguing, and how is that helping anyone or glorifying Christ at all? But at the same time, didn't God create this diversity? Because I don't say all I say just to raise eyebrows or  tempers, or to play devil's advocate. I mean, I have been thinking on most of this stuff for a few years now. Is it wrong to come to a different conclusion? I don't think anything I've said is heretical... But I don't want to get all maudlin, so<br>
<br>
Oh well. Something else to pray about.<br>
<br>
I got a message from my advisor in Scotland today. And I am getting quite excited about the possibility of studying over there! Like, maybe it is for real. Maybe I can actually do this. Maybe they'll REALLY accept me!!!<br>
<br>
Well, I've lost my train  of thought. And I should at least watch that other movie tonight before I go to sleep, so I can write the paper tomorrow. Did you know I have like 3 weeks left in this term? It's crazy! And that makes me all the closer to graduating! Yahooooooooo! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub78.ezboard.com/bchristlikebooklovers.showUserPublicProfile?gid=femalenomad>FemaleNomad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezHopeful</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#3333ff>(11/25/02 12:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fchristlikebookloversfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> 24th</span><hr size=1> Almost the 25th, but still the 24th for an hour yet.<br>
<br>
I am STILL trying to get  through the Fellowship of the Ring. I'm pretty well stuck in the middle. Bummer.<br>
<br>
But that's  not all I'm reading. I'm also reading &quot;Naturally Gifted,&quot; which is (of course) a book about the gifts God has given us, and finding and using them.  I'm still not exactly sure what my gifts are, so this is cool.<br>
<br>
I'm also reading a report on Women in Ministry from my denomination. It is vastly interesting. And a couple of items for another class - the Frankfurt and Lausanne covenants. I'm still on a quest for the Frankfurt one, though. Oh well.<br>
<br>
Soon (after school is finished for the term), I'll be reading that David Barton book. Just not yet, because I'm behind enough already!!!<br>
<br>
I scheduled my classes for next term. I'm pretty excited. Graduation looms ever nearer...and then there's Scotland, and before that, Australia...and now my friend's talking about a trip to Greece in July! I don't know if I can swing that...wonder if I can talk her into postponing it until next year? Unless my parents, in their ever-widening wisdom, see fit to give me a plane ticket to Greece for graduation. Not likely, is it? Well, we'll see.<br>
<br>
This week, I have to write a paper for one class, a thesis proposal, two simple papers for another class, and finish my movie journal for a third class. Then NEXT week, I have 2 more papers, and then 2 term papers (i.e.: BIG papers) to write. <br>
<br>
You know, every term I tell myself that this time it's going to be different. This time I'm not going to procrastinate. This time I'm going to work AHEAD. Well, I've been in school for all but four and a half years of my life (give or take), and I still haven't managed to get ahead but for my second term in Ireland, when I knew I had ten term papers to write. And then I was only 2 weeks ahead of the game. Argh.<br>
<br>
But next quarter really WILL be different.  It has to be, because I'm going to miss almost 2 weeks right in the middle when I go to Australia. And I have to have that work done ahead of time,  or else I'm going to be doing it on the plane (no thanks).<br>
<br>
Um, much as I love writing everything I think down, I should probably get to those papers. <br>
<br>
Ooh, Kirk Franklin's on the radio. *happy dance!* i SO need this! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bchristlikebooklovers.showUserPublicProfile?gid=femalenomad>FemaleNomad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezHopeful</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#3333ff>(12/6/02 10:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fchristlikebookloversfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> 6 December</span><hr size=1> Oh, wow! This new thing, with all the little emoticons and all this is AWESOME! Yahoo!<br>
<br>
It's been a couple of weeks, but I'm no closer to being finished with my schoolwork than I was when last I wrote.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Oh well. I mean, it all has to get done sooner or later, right? Well, that's what I'm hoping anyhow.<br>
<br>
Hm...what am I reading right now? Honey, you do NOT want to know. St. Paul at the Movies...which I am not exactly thrilled with. A New Religious American and lots of other Christianity/politics stuff...and something else, too. Oh, the Quotable Traveler. I want to buy this book for me for Christmas, but we have secret santas at work, so I suppose I can wait. But the quote book is just for fun, and it is quite fun!<br>
