<br>
Well, maybe not quite, but still...<br>
<br>
The good thing is, today I got a phone call from a long lost friend I have been missing and wishing I could talk to for about a million years. Two, at least. It was great to talk to him again, but it was kind of sad, too, because we're not as close as we used to be, and I MISS that friendship! He used to keep me accountable for so much; he's such a strong Christian. <br>
<br>
Once, I even though I would marry him. But now that's not the case. Still and all, I miss him. I miss having that spiritual voice in my life. Because, let's be honest, my spiritual voice has laryngitis. I'm afraid it might be permanent. <br>
<br>
Today I had only one class, and in that class I just realized how much I hate it. Really truly. It's a class on folk religions, world religions, etc. And it is SO not about that! It's about the theory of religion and how to map out what a religion is/does/appears to be. Forgive me, but that's pretty lame. Religion is an awfully personal thing, and no two people are going to practice their faith, whatever it is, the same. I'd far prefer to actually LEARN about religions! For example, Islam. I know nothing about Islam. I'm 26 years old, and completely ignorant on this topic! Ugh.<br>
<br>
All in all, I am feeling pretty negative about my life in general. I am far from the Lord - and I'm mighty good at saying all the right things - even though I know I believe in Him, and have saving faith in Jesus Christ. But the rest of it, the relational part of it, is pretty much at a standstill. Has been for about a year. (Well, if I'm completely honest, it's been that way for about.....five years?) I mean, I have moments, but in general, my faith is empty and dying. It's pathetic. Here I am at a seminary where I finally feel at home, learning from some truly excellent professors. I have a good job in a bookstore. I have friends, travel plans, and future goals. WHAT IS MY PROBLEM??!?<br>
<br>
Anyway, I might be pouring out my guts here pretty often for awhile. If y'all read this, feel free to comment at will. If you don't, that's cool, too. I don't care.<br>
<br>
Reading....I forgot a book: A Return to Modesty. Good stuff. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bchristlikebooklovers.showUserPublicProfile?gid=laughinglauraj>laughinglauraj</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezHappy</span><br>  Posts: 79<br> <font color=#3333ff>(2/14/03 10:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fchristlikebookloversfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: 13 Feb</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:blue;font-family:comic sans ms;">Well, Amy, I feel like that sometimes too.  You know what I do...I sit in my room and reread the gospels-the crucifixion scene.  I try to picture it in my head as I read about the betrayal and the death.  By the time I finish the first one, I have a new gratitude and a new appreciation.  Then I pray.  That's what works for me.  I just need to keep the gift that came through his suffering fresh in my head--to remember the sacrifice, etc.  <br>
We sing this song &quot;Don't let me walk too far from Calvary.&quot;  I love it b.c it talks about remembering the sacrifice.  I think if we keep that in mind, we can't help but feel that enthusiasm of our salvation.</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bchristlikebooklovers.showUserPublicProfile?gid=femalenomad>FemaleNomad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezHopeful</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#3333ff>(5/4/03 3:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fchristlikebookloversfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=24.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> 4 May 03</span><hr size=1> Okay, so I'm supposed to be packing right now, but I can't seem to make myself do it.<br>
<br>
Laura, even though I never said it then, I wanted to thank you for your thoughts. Your encouragement was something I needed to hear.<br>
<br>
Anyway. It's been a few months. What's new here? Um, I received my first-ever rejection slip. Honestly. I've never been rejected from ANYTHING I wanted before. It was a slightly humbling experience to receive that too-thin envelope from University of Edinburgh. Just looking at it, I knew I didn't get in. <br>
<br>
But, you know, about two weeks after I sent my application in, I decided I didn't really want to go. That I wanted to stay here. Get a life. A real job, put down roots, etc. So, it wasn't a huge let-down. Just kind of a surprise.<br>
<br>
My mom said the same thing. &quot;This is your first rejection slip, Amy!&quot; Yeah. We talked about framing it, like businesses frame their first dollar of profit. lol!<br>
<br>
Anyway. It's 3pm. I REALLY should finish packing. <br>
<br>
Right now, I am reading.....Word of Honor (NElson DeMille - eh), Two Towers (still), and a few million textbooks I don't want. And something else, I think. Oh, Urban Chic - a girl's guide to city living on next to nothing. Pretty fun.<br>
<br>
Now I AM going to pack! I AM!!!<br>
